# Web visualization UX/layout standards

## Scope / resources

- This tool targets traffic visualization for Kubernetes **Ingress / Service / Endpoints**, Istio **VirtualService / DestinationRule**, and Contour **Gateway (HTTPProxy)**.
- If a VirtualService references `spec.gateways`, an Istio **Gateway** node must be rendered and linked (Gateway → VirtualService) to make the entry semantics explicit.
- Adding new resource kinds must update: parser → graph → node UI → harness spec.

## Import experience

- Multi-file upload must support: click-select + drag-drop, and should auto-refresh graph after import.
- Folder import must be supported (directory picker + drag-drop a folder) and preserve each file’s relative path when available.
- Show import state (file count + short list of names).
- Keep left panel actions minimal; avoid “extra clicks”.
- Imported file names must be bound into each Area header (“来源文件”) right after import; no “unbound” state on file import.

## Layout readability (must)

- Multiple ingresses must be clearly separated (partition/swimlane). Never merge nodes across ingresses if it breaks ownership clarity.
- Avoid heavy overlaps on initial load; keep generous vertical spacing.
- Prefer a visible region background per ingress (group/region block with subtle tint + border + title).
- If there are many routes, prefer a dedicated Route node per path (Host → Route → Service) instead of stacking edge labels.
- Areas should use a non-flow layout: **at most 4 areas per row**, auto-wrap to multiple rows, and area height/width should expand to fit content.
- Example tier lanes (must): if imported file paths contain `01-* / 02-* / 03-*` tier directories, lay Areas out in **three fixed columns** (01 left, 02 middle, 03 right), **one Area per row** per column; within a column, `Active01` must appear above `Active02`.
- Contour Gateway principle (must): **Ingress → Service → Contour Gateway** must be represented.
- Contour Gateway layout (must): inside its Area, keep strict left-to-right order: **Contour Gateway → HTTPProxy → Host → Route → Service → Endpoints**.
- Istio Gateway principle (must): if Service name equals Istio Gateway name (same namespace), render a cross-area edge **Service → Istio Gateway**. If multiple VirtualServices reference the same gateway, match by **path-native tokens split ONLY by "/"** (Ingress path segments vs VS match path segments), connect only to the best match; if no match, do not auto-wire (user can add manual edge).

## Node content (must)

- Ingress: name, ns, class, LB/status IP, TLS blocks (secret + hosts)
- VirtualService: name, ns, hosts, HTTP matches (path), destination service + port
- Contour Gateway (HTTPProxy): name, ns, fqdn/hosts（如可得）, HTTP prefix matches (path), destination service + port
- DestinationRule: subsets shown on related Service card when possible
- Host: host, ingress name, TLS secret match (or explicit “no TLS”)
- Service: name, ns, type, clusterIP, spec ports, ingress backend port
- Endpoints: service context, pod IPs, port/protocol

## Canvas UX (must)

- Manual edges: user can connect via handles; manual edges must be visually distinct (grey dashed) and survive YAML refresh when endpoints remain valid.
- All node types that appear on canvas must expose visible handles (at least left+right) so users can manually connect nodes, including across Areas.
- Toolbar: canvas operations (PNG/export/save/open) should be compact by default and must not obstruct the topology.

## Visual identity (must)

- Nodes must be highly distinguishable even when zoomed out: left accent bar + strong title row + consistent typography.
- Automatic edges must be directional (arrow markers) and color-coded by semantics.
- Manual edges must remain visually distinct from computed edges (grey dashed, arrow) and remain after refresh when valid.

